class=title>   Re: Would Orion Really Work?</span><hr size=1> A couple of good bits from &quot;the Orion Lemmings' Bible&quot;<br>
<br>
Ch 1, P 4<br>
&quot;For about one 3-thousandth of a second, the plasma stagnates against the pusher plate at a temperature of about 120,000 degrees. The time is too short for heat to penetrate the pusher, so the ship is able to survive an extended series of pulses, the way someone can run across a bed of coals without getting burned. Even on an ambitious inteplanetary mission, involving several thousand explosions, the total plasma-pusher interaction time amounts to less than one second. The high temperatures are isolated, both in time and distance, from the ship.&quot;<br>
<br>
Ch 2, P 18<br>
&quot;By the time we started work on Orion,&quot; explains Ted, &quot;there were a whole lot of checked-out possibilities for tailoring the effects of the primary by fiddling around with the design so it would change the relative fraction of energy, in neutrons, in penetrating gammas, high-speed debris, and so on. We could pick out what we wanted, which was momentum stretched out over a long enough time so the pressures weren't intolerable but short enough so that the heat transfer wasn't intolerable either. We had a whole array of possible ways of designing the explosives to do that.&quot;<br>
<br>
 I probably need to explain for the dense, that this isn't fiction, made up to sell a book. Dyson wrote that after interviewing people who had worked on the original design works and after reviewing the technical articles -all of which are referenced in the book, and all of which stand up to review today.<br>
 Even though they didn't build a ship to test their theories, they were knowledgeable enough in their fields to say with certainty that there were ways to make it work. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=q66stang>Q66stang</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Cadet</span><br>  Posts: 43<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(5/20/03 11:59 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=319.topic&index=168>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: &quot;Problems With The Orion Spacecraft&quot;  article</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em> Even though they didn't build a ship to test their theories, they were knowledgeable enough in their fields to say with certainty that there were ways to make it work.</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
