<br>
blah blah blah yada yada yada....<br>
You're crowing over having reduced &quot;certainty to possibility&quot; while you haven't done anything other than make noise.<br>
 You have proven not a thing, except that some people will make endless noise about things they know little or nothing about and don't care to put any work into.<br>
<br>
 I doubt anybody -even Taylor or Dyson would have said that there was a certainty that EPPP or Orion would work. As was said here, there's a certainty that there's a strong possibility that it would match the designs and specifications they worked out in the early studies.<br>
 Only a fool said it was certain, and only a fool picks it apart as if it were, and makes assertions about things they haven't studied and makes accusations of fraud and ignorance in their fields against scientists who worked on a program the detractors haven't studied.<br>
<br>
The person over at SDC (who incidentally lets their real name be known) is using the same flawed reasoning you are: the slightest doubt means total certainty against the proposal, and that circumstantial evidence extracted from considerations about completely different applications (large weapon effects against ground targets in atmosphere, are relevant when thinking about loosely related conditions (plasma produced by a remote, small device, impacting on a pusher).<br>
<br>
 Contrary to my boat not floating very well, I've just started to pull strips of caulk out of his waterline, while putting mine into the water.<br>
<br>
No, simply because they didn't do nuclear tests pertaining directly to this application doesn't mean that the plasma gun tests, computer codes they developed, and other evidence leading up to the conditions the plate would experience is irrelevant.<br>
Research methods say that if models match the conditions of the gas gun tests, and that they can precisely create and direct the prompt radiation to tailor the nature of the plasma as desired, that there's near-certainty that their models accurately predict the interactions at the interface.<br>
<br>
The fact that neither you nor David M. (Maddad)  has shown clear understanding of how they actually proposed to make it work, or done any sort of study pertaining to the actual Orion work (or are even aware of the volume of it) shows that you aren't to be taken too seriously. <p></p><i></i></td></tr></table> </td></tr></table> <table border=0 width=95%><tr><td align=left valign="top">  Page <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showMessageRange?topicID=319.topic&start=1&stop=20>1</a><a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showMessageRange?topicID=319.topic&start=21&stop=40>2</a><a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showMessageRange?topicID=319.topic&start=41&stop=60>3</a><a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showMessageRange?topicID=319.topic&start=61&stop=80>4</a><a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showMessageRange?topicID=319.topic&start=81&stop=100>5</a><a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showMessageRange?topicID=319.topic&start=101&stop=120>6</a><a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showMessageRange?topicID=319.topic&start=121&stop=140>7</a><a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showMessageRange?topicID=319.topic&start=141&stop=160>8</a> <b>9</b>  </td><td align=right valign="top"><a href="http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showPrevMessage?topicID=319.topic"> << Prev Topic</a>&nbsp;| <a href="http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showNextMessage?topicID=319.topic"> Next Topic >> </a><br><br><a self href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=319.topic&index=167><img src=http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/addreply3.jpg border=0 alt="Add Reply"></a> </td></tr></table><br><table width=95% border=0><td valign="top"> <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.emailToFriend?topicID=319.topic><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/image/email.gif border=0